summaries.title: Balancing Research and Cultural Expectations
summaries.summaryText: Priya balanced heavy research commitments with cultural obligations, feeling pressure to excel as a first-gen Indian-American student in tech. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Integrating Mental Health Advocacy with STEM Identity
summaries.summaryText: Sarah described bridging mental health awareness into STEM culture through peer-led workshops. [Part 1/4]

summaries.summaryText: Peer mentors and cultural centers helped Luis navigate isolation as a first-gen Latino student. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Family Support and Pressure as a Dual Motivation
summaries.summaryText: As a first-generation student, Daniels parents provided emotional encouragement but limited academic guidance. Their sacrifices motivated him, though he expressed anxiety about failing to meet expectations. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Navigating Gender Bias in Research Environments
summaries.summaryText: She recounted experiences where her technical contributions were overlooked and strategies she used to assert confidence. [Part 4/4]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniels experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Marias reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyahs mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniels experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 3]

themes.title: First-Generation Adaptation to STEM Rigor
themes.description: Luiss story demonstrates resilience through peer and cultural support. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 3]

quotes.quoteText: My parents always say 'you represent the family'it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Priya describing family expectations.

quotes.quoteText: Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel describing peer mentorship as a belonging intervention.

quotes.quoteText: It took me a year to realize struggling is normal  not a sign that Im not supposed to be here. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel describing the turning point after joining peer mentoring programs.

quotes.quoteText: I realized I had access to engineering summer camps that most of my friends never even heard of  thats when privilege clicked for me. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Ethan reflecting on his exposure to early STEM opportunities.

quotes.quoteText: Seeing other Latina engineers at the SHPE conference made me feel like Im not alone  like I really do belong in this field. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on peer support and cultural representation.

quotes.quoteText: I love leading projects, but its exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Aaliyah describing the advocacy work tied to her leadership role.

quotes.quoteText: Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Daniel describing peer mentorship as a belonging intervention.

quotes.quoteText: Mentorship is how we survive here  sharing what weve learned keeps us going when the system doesnt always see us. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Aaliyah on the value of mentorship networks.

quotes.quoteText: I wish there were a clearer path for first-gen students to find mentorship  it feels like everyone else already knows the rules. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Maria discussing gaps in support infrastructure.

quotes.quoteText: No one in my family went to college, so I didnt even know how office hours worked my first semester. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Maria describing her initial confusion with academic expectations as a first-gen student.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it  like Im pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Daniel discussing his sense of imposter syndrome in engineering coursework.

quotes.quoteText: My parents dont really understand what I study, but they tell everyone Im going to be an engineer  that means a lot, but its also scary. [Context 2]

quotes.quoteText: At first I thought I wasnt smart enough, but then I realized everyones struggling; we just dont talk about it. [Context 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Integrate Wellness Programming into STEM Curriculum
areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Create service-learning credit for mentorship and advocacy roles
Include advocacy experience in leadership award criteria

areasForImprovement.title: Normalize Academic Struggle Through Faculty Messaging
areasForImprovement.description: Faculty can help counter imposter syndrome by sharing personal learning experiences, highlighting that mastery develops over time and through mistakes. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Encourage faculty to include learning journeys in course introductions
Develop short workshops on inclusive teaching practices
